Each module drops its code under `internal/` (and, for some, top-level
files like this README or `.gitignore`). Selecting a module does not wire
it into your HTTP routes or call sites for you — for example, the
`idempotency` and `ratelimit` middleware are generated but not attached to
any handler, and `webhook`'s provider verifiers are generated but not
mounted on any endpoint. Wire them into your `cmd/api/main.go` (or
wherever you build your router) as your application needs them.

## Migrations

Some modules (e.g. `ledger`, `audit`) generate their own SQL under
`migrations/`. Each such file is numbered `0001` relative to that
module's own migration history, not a project-wide sequence — selecting
more than one of these modules means more than one file named
`0001_*_schema.sql`. Most tools sort by full filename and handle that
fine; a tool that treats the leading digits as a single, strictly
unique version number across the whole directory (e.g. golang-migrate's
default numeric scheme) will not. Check your migration tool's
assumptions before running more than one module's migrations together.
Keel does not run migrations itself — applying them, with whatever tool
you choose, is up to you.
